			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>DrAST: An Inspection Tool for Attributed Syntax Trees (Tool Demo)</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JoelLindholm.html">Joel Lindholm</a>, <a href="../profile/JohanThorsberg.html">Johan Thorsberg</a>, <a href="../profile/GörelHedin.html">Görel Hedin</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997378">10.1145/2997364.2997378</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> DrAST is a tool for inspecting attributed syntax trees, i.e., language implementation tooling.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Attributed syntax trees/attribute grammars often encode static semantics, which the tool helps understand and debug.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It supports analysis/debugging of language specifications and their attributed tree structures.
</li></ul></li></ul>
